        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2022-01-24 19:32:27.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 12:\n\nSorry for the brain dump here, I am trying to come to terms to the work.    These are some items that I just don't have them clear in my mind.   \n\n1. I think the policy_type_impl is not very intuitive or accurate as a name, renaming it to ruleset of something of that sort if that's the intent may be more meaningful if the intent is to further partition the type into subgroups of policies under that policy type.\n\n2. Have 1 complete realistic example for apex, I don't see xacml or drools going this route for provisioning at least in the immediate term, so those examples are not necessary.   Something that shows the value added that cannot be simply resolved with {tosca-policy-type:version, tosca-policy:version} definition pairs.\n\n3. A complete \"yaml/json\" example of a apex policy-type/policy-type-impl/policy accompanied by junits that show how they relate to each other would be very helpful.\n\n4. Should the \"policy_type_impl\" be a tosca structure/construct as tosca-policy-type and tosca-policy.   It seems that it is an arbitrary structure but not tosca based.   Since we move to tosca, wouldn't it make sense to use tosca definitions.\n\n5. The \"type_impl\" in policy_type_impl is confusing as it takes actual (numeric or string) values more similar to a tosca-policy rather than a type\n\n6. Along those lines it makes more sense at least in my mind to define its own tosca entity, for example policy-ruleset-type to define the types to be used and a policy-ruleset to specify the actual values (equivalently to the current tosca-policy).\n\n7. How does the policy-type-impl is administered, this adds complexity for the policy designer, because will need to track the tosca-policy-type, the policy_type_impl, and the tosca-policy to make sense on what's going on in a system.    This seems to me is going to be difficult to administer in the clamp gui.    For example a change in a tosca-policy-type-impl will apply to many policies underneath.    Further, those deployed policies would need to be updated under the reference policy type.   How this scenario is supposed to be handled?\n\n8. How are changes in the policy-type-impl are administered with different versions?   And if there are different policy-type-impl versions, how does the pap know which one to apply?   Right now policy types and policies are immutable and versioned.   Since the policy-type-impl are values (not types, ie. 6, \"west\") there may be multiple copies of it that could be attached to the same policy type for different flavors, how will those cases be handled? \n\n9. I feel pdp-type (in tosca-policy-type-impl) should not be at the tosca-policy-type / tosca-policy level, I think so far we managed to have those structures agnostic of the pdp-type, not sure if this should be part of it.",
        "patchset_number": 12
      },
